Welcome to the course!
Dear Students,
Welcome to what promises to be a unique and personally meaningful semester! Classes begin in just one week, and I wanted to share three essential insights that will set you up for success from day one.
This Course Is About Your Real Life, Not Abstract Theory
Unlike traditional ethics courses, you won't be memorizing philosophical theories or solving hypothetical moral puzzles. Instead, you'll be developing a practical toolkit for navigating the ethical complexity you actually face—when loyalty to a friend conflicts with professional responsibilities, or when environmental concerns clash with career pressures.
No prior coursework in philosophy or ethics is required. This course is designed for students at all levels and across all disciplines. You will need:
Willingness to engage in honest self-reflection
Ability to identify a genuine ethical dilemma from your own experience
Openness to exploring your own decision-making patterns
Commitment to sustained engagement with complex ideas over the semester"*
Key insight: Choose a dilemma you genuinely care about with real stakes. The success of your entire semester depends on selecting something that matters to you personally and can sustain deep exploration.
AI Is Your Thinking Partner, Not Your Shortcut
You'll be working with AI throughout this course, but not to generate answers for you. Think of AI as a collaborative partner that helps you explore ethical complexity in ways that would be difficult alone—challenging your assumptions, pushing your reasoning, and helping you see your dilemma from multiple angles.
Essential practice: Create "checkpoints" every 10-15 minutes of AI conversation. Save these summaries as files so you can resume work across sessions without losing context. This isn't just good organization—it's how you'll document your evolving thinking process for your final self-assessment.
You're Building an Algorithm for Ethical Decision-Making
We're treating ethics as an evolving algorithm—a decision-making process that guides how you navigate challenges when multiple values compete for your attention. You'll discover the heuristics (mental shortcuts) you already use, then systematically examine them against formal philosophical frameworks.
What this means: Instead of traditional tests and grades, you'll demonstrate your learning through self-assessment, making a case for your own intellectual growth with evidence from your work throughout the semester.
Staying Connected in an Online Course
I know online asynchronous courses can feel isolating, and it's remarkably easy to fall behind when there aren't regular class meetings to keep you on track. I've designed this course specifically to address these challenges:
You're not learning alone: You'll be reading course assignments in a shared, collaborative browser app called Perusall, where you will be asked to share your thoughts about the text, and where you can read the musings of your classmates. Additionally, around the middle of the semester, you will be invited to share some of your work in a shared Google folder and examine the work others submit. I am calling this a Gallery Walk, much like what it would be like if we were to stage our work in a museum or art gallery for others to consider.
Structured guidance: Every major task includes detailed AI prompts that guide you step-by-step through the process. You're never left wondering "what do I do next?"
Questions?
This approach may feel unfamiliar, but you're not alone. The course includes structured AI prompts to guide you through every phase, peer podcasts to hear how others wrestle with similar challenges, and my support when you need it. I've taught enough online courses to know where students typically struggle, and I've built support systems to catch you before you fall through the cracks.
I'm excited to see how your ethical reasoning develops this semester as you build tools you can actually use when things get complicated.
Oh, and by the way...
My name is Clayn Lambert. I am the department chair for Business and Support Services in the College of Technology. I have been teaching in the Technical General Education program since August of 2002. My background started in English and teaching development writing courses, but over the years, I have expanded my repertoire into the social sciences. I created TGE 1257 in 2013 and have overseen much of the development of the course over the years. 

P.S. If you're feeling uncertain about whether this course is right for you, that's normal. The most meaningful learning often happens when we're working with genuine complexity rather than easy answers. Trust the process—and reach out if you need support along the way.
Course Grading Policy
Overview: Self-Assessment Approach
This course uses self-assessment rather than traditional point-based grading. There are no quizzes, tests, rubrics, or point totals. Instead, you will demonstrate your learning through sustained philosophical work documented across seven modules, then make an evidence-based case for your final grade.

Why Self-Assessment?
Traditional grading encourages students to figure out what the instructor wants. But ethical thinking requires you to grapple with genuine uncertainty, make discoveries you can defend, and develop your own intellectual voice. Self-assessment supports authentic engagement with philosophical complexity rather than performance for points.

How Grading Works
Throughout the Semester (Parts 0-6):
Complete all module activities and document your work in your shared Google Drive folder
Engage authentically with readings, AI conversations, peer interactions, and philosophical exploration
Build an evidence trail that demonstrates your intellectual journey
At Semester's End (Part 7):
Review your complete body of work from Parts 0-6
Write a self-assessment (1-2 pages) that includes:
Your learning journey narrative (2-3 paragraphs)
3-5 specific evidence examples from your work with explanations of what they demonstrate
Your proposed grade with justification
Schedule a collaborative conversation (15-20 minutes) with Dr. Lambert to discuss your self-assessment
Final Grade Determination: Your final grade will be determined collaboratively based on:
Your self-assessment and proposed grade
The evidence you provide from your documented work
Our conversation about your learning

Making Your Case: Guidance Questions
Rather than prescribing what each letter grade "means," you'll make an argument for your grade based on evidence of your learning. Different students will make different cases—there's no single formula.
To make a compelling argument, you should be able to:
Point to specific evidence from your documented work (not general claims like "I worked hard")
Tell the story of your learning showing where you started and how your thinking evolved
Acknowledge both strengths and limitations honestly
Connect your evidence to the intellectual work we've done all semester
Questions to guide your grade proposal:
About Engagement:
Can you show moments where you genuinely wrestled with complexity rather than seeking easy answers?
Where did you lean into discomfort rather than away from it?
Did you explore your dilemma with genuine curiosity or go through the motions?
About Growth:
What did you understand at the end that you couldn't have articulated at the beginning?
Where did your thinking become more sophisticated or nuanced?
Can you trace specific shifts in how you understand your ethical reasoning?
About Honesty:
Did you document your actual thinking, including contradictions and unresolved tensions?
Can you point to places where you were honest about gaps between your ideals and behavior?
Did you acknowledge what remains difficult rather than forcing tidy conclusions?
About Integration:
How did philosophical frameworks change how you see your dilemma?
Can you show evidence of working with philosophical concepts, not just about them?
Where did frameworks illuminate patterns you were using unconsciously?
About Intellectual Risk:
When did you push beyond your comfort zone?
Where did you challenge your own assumptions?
Can you show evidence of exploration that surprised you?
About Documentation:
Is your evidence trail complete enough to make your case?
Do your AI transcripts show genuine thinking or surface-level exchanges?
Can someone else follow your intellectual journey through your work?
The collaborative conversation:
Our conversation isn't an interrogation—it's a collaborative discussion about what your evidence shows. I might ask:
"Can you walk me through this piece of evidence and what it demonstrates?"
"What surprised you most about your own learning?"
"Where do you feel you took intellectual risks?"
"What would you do differently if you were starting the course now?"
"How does this evidence support the grade you're proposing?"
Your grade will emerge from the strength of your argument and the evidence you provide, not from whether you hit predetermined benchmarks.

Common Misconceptions About Self-Assessment
❌ "I completed all the work" ≠ automatic high grade (completion is baseline; depth of engagement matters)
❌ "I resolved my dilemma" ≠ success (some dilemmas don't resolve; understanding why is learning)
❌ "I struggled" ≠ failure (struggle with evidence of genuine engagement is valuable)
❌ "I worked really hard" ≠ sufficient justification (what did that work produce in terms of learning?)
✅ "Here's where my thinking shifted, here's the evidence, here's what it demonstrates" = strong argument

Important Notes
Completion Requirements:
All seven modules must be completed to receive a passing grade
The collaborative conversation (Part 7) is required and serves as the course's final exam
Missing documentation makes it impossible to assess learning
Honesty Matters More Than Perfection:
You won't be penalized for acknowledging struggles, unresolved tensions, or patterns you're not proud of
Authentic self-reflection is valued more than presenting an idealized version of your learning
The goal is understanding your ethical complexity, not solving it perfectly
Grade Proposals:
Your proposed grade is taken seriously but is not automatically accepted
Our collaborative conversation may result in adjustments based on evidence discussion
Be prepared to defend your grade with specific examples from your work
If you're uncertain about your grade after reviewing your work, schedule office hours before the final conversation
Academic Integrity:
All work must be your own authentic thinking
AI is used as a thinking partner to help you think, not to generate your thoughts for you
Plagiarism or fabricated evidence will result in course failure

Timeline for Self-Assessment
