My Commitment
I'll monitor your progress, respond to emails within 24 hours (business days), and reach out if I'm concerned. But you're adults—I won't chase you if you choose not to engage. I'm here to support your success, but you have to show up for it.
What This Means for You:
You're not working in isolation. I'm watching your progress and will reach out if I'm concerned. But you also have agency—you can work at your own pace and request help whenever you need it. The shared Drive folder means we're in this together throughout the semester, not just at grading deadlines.
Course Alignment Documentation
General Education Course Outcomes:
 
Upon completion of a course in this category, students are able to demonstrate at least five (5) of the following competencies.
Recognize and describe humanistic, historical, or artistic works within problems and patterns of the human experience.
Distinguish and apply methodologies, approaches, or traditions specific to the discipline.
Differentiate formal, conceptual, and technical elements specific to the discipline.
Analyze, evaluate, and interpret texts, objects, events, or ideas in their cultural, intellectual or historical contexts.
Interpret artistic or humanistic works through the creation of art, language, or performance.
Develop critical perspectives or arguments about the subject matter, grounded in evidence-based analysis.
Demonstrate self-reflection, widened perspective, and respect for diverse viewpoints.
Course Level Outcomes
 
Utilize intellectual tools for making reasoned, ethically‐grounded decisions, within the spaces they will occupy (work, business, home, etc.)
Recognize and analyze ethical issues in the workplace
Explore the foundations of classical and modern versions of ethical theory, and then proceed to its general application within business, work, and casual settings
Consider and evaluate specific issues faced in the past by companies and individuals, as well as projecting into issues that they (the students themselves) are likely to face going forward




General Education Learning Outcome Alignment


HWK 1: Distinguish and apply methodologies
HWK 2: Differentiate formal, conceptual, and technical elements
HWK 3: Analyze texts/events in context
HWK 4: Develop critical perspectives grounded in evidence
HWK 5: Self-reflection, widened perspective, respect for diverse viewpoints
Part 0
Introduction to philosophical methodology: excavating existing reasoning vs. applying theory top-down
Distinguishing ethics from law, personal preference, and corporate policy
Annotating Garlikov in collaborative context; analyzing philosophical arguments about studying ethics
Beginning evidence-based reflection through documented AI conversations
Surfacing pre-existing ethical foundations before formal study; recognizing multiple annotation perspectives in Perusall
Part 1
Applying dilemma identification methodology: 5 criteria for genuine ethical complexity; devil's advocate approach
Distinguishing genuine dilemmas from practical problems, preferences, or constrained choices
Analyzing Holt's framework for ethical dilemmas; applying concepts to lived experience
Building evidence: documented AI conversations testing dilemma against criteria; justifying why situation qualifies
Self-reflection on personal decision-making power; recognizing stakeholder perspectives create competing obligations
Part 2
Applying heuristic excavation methodology: systematic interview process to surface decision patterns
Differentiating aspirational values, character traits, and behavioral decision rules ("if/then" patterns)
Analyzing own decision-making in cultural/professional context; recognizing origin stories of ethical patterns
Evidence-based analysis: 25-35 specific heuristics with concrete examples from actual behavior
Deep self-reflection distinguishing ideals from actual practice; recognizing contradictions and gaps in own reasoning
Part 3
Applying conflict mapping methodology: identifying where heuristics/roles create tension; choosing representation format
Distinguishing types of ethical conflict: role-based, principle-based, stakeholder-based
Analyzing own conflicts in cultural/professional/relational contexts; examining why specific tensions exist
Evidence-grounded map: connecting abstract tensions to concrete dilemma moments; documenting emotional/practical stakes
Self-reflection on internal contradictions; respecting complexity without forcing resolution
Part 4
Applying strategic sequencing methodology: matching frameworks to personal tensions and learning preferences
Understanding 10 distinct frameworks as different conceptual/technical approaches to ethics
Analyzing which frameworks historically address which types of ethical questions
Evidence-based roadmap: justifying sequence with specific reference to conflict map and learning goals
Self-reflection on learning style; recognizing frameworks offer diverse legitimate perspectives
Part 5
Applying archaeological methodology 10 times: discovering where each framework already operates in own thinking
Differentiating 10 frameworks: Deontology, Virtue Ethics, Utilitarianism, Social Contract, De Beauvoir, Nietzsche, Marxism, Environmental Ethics, Bioethics, Natural Law
Analyzing each framework in: intellectual history, cultural context, application to own dilemma; Perusall annotations examining frameworks in original texts
Evidence-based excavation reports: documenting specific heuristics reflecting each framework; tracing philosophical origins; Gallery Walk peer analysis
Sustained self-reflection across 10 frameworks; recognizing peers' different excavations in Gallery Walk; respecting philosophical diversity
Part 6
Applying synthesis methodology: reviewing 10 framework explorations to assess evolution in understanding
Comparing/contrasting formal elements across frameworks; recognizing complementary and conflicting approaches
Analyzing how frameworks illuminate or complicate dilemma in different ways; examining philosophical tensions in personal context
Evidence-based synthesis: updated conflict map showing which tensions are  resolved, reframed, or complicated; documented journey review with specific examples
Deep self-reflection on intellectual transformation; acknowledging what remains unresolved; respecting ongoing complexity
Part 7
Demonstrating command of course methodologies through self-assessment narrative
Articulating understanding of different frameworks and their technical/conceptual distinctions
Situating own learning journey in broader philosophical and personal context
Evidence-based grade justification: specific examples from 7 modules demonstrating engagement and growth
Comprehensive self-reflection on semester; collaborative conversation respecting instructor perspective on learning

Course-level Learning Outcomes


LO1: Utilize intellectual tools for reasoned, ethically-grounded decisions
LO2: Recognize and analyze ethical issues in workplace
LO3: Explore foundations of ethical theory and application
LO4: Consider/evaluate past cases and project into future issues
Part 0
Introduction to "archaeological" approach to ethical reasoning; AI as thinking partner
Identifying ethical complexity in lived experience
Preview of course's framework exploration approach
Beginning to examine pre-existing ethical foundations
Part 1
Developing criteria for genuine ethical dilemmas; using AI for discovery and critical testing
Identifying authentic workplace/personal dilemmas with competing roles and real stakes
Understanding what makes situations ethically complex (foundation for later theory)
Analyzing student's own current/ongoing dilemma; stress-testing through devil's advocate
Part 2
Distinguishing aspirational values from actual decision-making patterns; "if/then" heuristic mapping
Surfacing actual workplace decision rules across professional roles
Uncovering informal ethical frameworks as preparation for formal theory exploration
Examining student's own past behavior patterns and decision histories
Part 3
Identifying where reasoning patterns create competing demands; representing complexity visually/textually
Mapping workplace tensions between roles, values, and stakeholder obligations
Recognizing philosophical tensions before having formal language for them
Connecting abstract tensions to concrete moments in student's dilemma
Part 4
Strategic sequencing of learning based on personal tensions and preferences
Matching workplace conflicts to potentially relevant philosophical approaches
Designing personalized roadmap through 10 frameworks based on student's conflict map
Anticipating which theories might address student's specific ongoing dilemma
Part 5
Archaeological excavation through all 10 frameworks: Deontology, Virtue Ethics, Utilitarianism, Social Contract, De Beauvoir, Nietzsche, Marxism, Environmental Ethics, Bioethics, Natural Law
Discovering where each framework already operates in workplace reasoning patterns
Primary location of LO3: Deep exploration of classical and modern ethical theories through personalized sequence; tracing origins of philosophical patterns in student's thinking
Applying each framework to illuminate student's dilemma; peer gallery walk examining multiple cases
Part 6
Integrating tools from 10 frameworks; identifying which tensions resolved/complicated/reframed
Synthesizing workplace ethical analysis across multiple philosophical lenses
Comparing and contrasting frameworks; recognizing complementary and conflicting approaches
Determining next steps for student's dilemma based on evolved understanding; identifying ongoing questions
Part 7
Demonstrating capacity to use philosophical tools for continued ethical reasoning
Articulating growth in recognizing and analyzing workplace ethical complexity
Reflecting on which theoretical foundations resonate most and why
Evaluating transformation in understanding of own case from beginning to end of semester

 
