Why This Variety Matters:
Different ways of demonstrating learning: Written analysis, visual representation, conversational exploration, peer engagement
Authentic to philosophical practice: Philosophers write, debate, diagram, reflect, and engage in dialogue
Accommodates diverse strengths: Students can excel through different modalities
Prevents gaming: No single "type" of performance determines success
Appropriateness for Course Level (1000-Level General Education)
 
Developmentally Appropriate:
Starts with familiar territory (own life, own thinking) rather than abstract philosophical concepts
Scaffolds complexity gradually:
Parts 0-1: Identify and describe
Parts 2-3: Analyze patterns
Part 4: Strategic planning
Part 5: Apply and discover
Parts 6-7: Synthesize and reflect
Provides extensive support:
AI as thinking partner throughout
Structured prompts for all major activities
Model questions rather than expecting students to generate frameworks independently
Readings introduce concepts that students then discover in their own thinking
Doesn't require prior philosophy knowledge:
Archaeological approach means discovering concepts in own patterns rather than learning theory first
Perusall annotations help students collectively make sense of readings
Multiple attempts/explorations allow for learning through iteration
Emphasizes process over product:
Documentation valued over polished final products
Honest struggle and unresolved tensions are legitimate outcomes
Growth mindset embedded in assessment approach
Rigorous but Accessible:
Sustained engagement with complex ideas (10 philosophical frameworks over semester)
Requires sophisticated thinking (analyzing own reasoning, integrating multiple frameworks, constructing evidence-based arguments)
But doesn't assume expertise: Students work with concepts at their own level, guided by structured support
Authentic assessment: Rather than testing whether students can define "categorical imperative," asks whether they can recognize where Kantian thinking already appears in their own reasoning
Formative vs. Summative Balance
Formative (Low-Stakes, Learning-Focused):
Perusall annotations (practice analytical reading)
AI conversations (think-out-loud exploration)
Gallery Walk (learn from peers)
Part 6 synthesis (review and integration)
Summative (Evidence-Building, Evaluative):
Complete documentation trail (Parts 0-6 collectively)
Self-Assessment + Collaborative Conversation (Part 7)



Alignment with Course Philosophy
The assessment sequence and variety directly support the archaeological approach:
You can't excavate what you haven't documented → Continuous documentation throughout
Discovery happens through conversation → AI-facilitated interviews and peer engagement
Complexity requires multiple representations → Visual, written, conversational modalities
Learning is non-linear → Students choose framework sequence; unresolved tensions are valid
Growth requires honest self-assessment → Culminating reflection on entire journey
Standard 3.5
Tracking Learning Progress and Timely Feedback
