Part 7 preparation
Practice articulating your learning before final conversation

Feedback Opportunities Throughout the Semester
Unlike traditional courses where feedback comes only on graded assignments, you receive multiple types of feedback continuously:
Peer Feedback (Asynchronous, Throughout Semester)


Where:
Perusall annotations (12+ readings)
Gallery Walk (Part 5)
What You Receive:
Responses to your annotations from classmates
Questions that push your thinking further
Alternative perspectives on concepts you're exploring
Examples of how others are excavating their own patterns
Timing:
Perusall: Ongoing as peers engage with readings
Gallery Walk: After your 3rd framework exploration
How to Use It:
Notice which of your ideas generate discussion
Consider questions peers raise about your thinking
Observe different approaches to similar philosophical concepts
AI-Generated Feedback (Immediate, Throughout Semester)


Where:
All AI-facilitated activities (Parts 0-7)
What You Receive:
Probing questions that reveal gaps in your thinking
Summaries that mirror your ideas back for examination
Challenges to assumptions you're making
Prompts to go deeper or get more specific
Timing: Immediate during each AI conversation
How to Use It:
If AI repeatedly asks for clarification, you may be staying too abstract
If AI summary doesn't match your intent, you may need to articulate more clearly
If conversation feels surface-level, push yourself to engage more substantively
Instructor Feedback on Documentation (Formative, Ongoing)


Where:
Your shared Google Drive folder
What You Receive:
Comments on documents indicating areas needing clarification, expansion, or revision
Questions highlighting where evidence is thin or claims need support
Recognition of particularly strong analytical moments
Gentle redirects if you're off-track
Timing:
Periodic throughout semester (Dr. Lambert reviews folders on rolling basis)
More frequent feedback available upon request during office hours
Intensive review before Part 7 self-assessment
How to Use It:
Check your folder regularly for comments
Respond to questions and revise as needed (documentation is living, not static)
Schedule office hours if you receive feedback you don't understand
Self-Monitoring Checkpoints (Built into Course Structure)


Devil's Advocate (Part 1):
Purpose: Stress-test your dilemma before building semester's work on it
Feedback: Reveals whether dilemma is substantial enough for sustained analysis
Action: Refine or choose different dilemma if needed
Heuristics Review (Part 2):
Purpose: Ensure you've identified actual patterns, not aspirational ones
Feedback: Gaps between what you claim and what evidence shows
Action: Return to AI interview to probe deeper if patterns seem shallow
Conflict Map Working Document (Part 3):
Purpose: Create referenceable summary of tensions
Feedback: Can you articulate tensions clearly enough to use them all semester?
Action: Revise until tensions are concrete and well-defined
Gallery Walk Reflection (Part 5):
Purpose: Compare your analytical depth to peers
Feedback: Are you excavating as deeply as others? Differently?
Action: Adjust approach for remaining framework explorations
Part 6 Journey Review:
Purpose: Assess how understanding has evolved
Feedback: Can you show clear growth from Parts 0-6?
Action: Identify gaps in documentation or reflection before Part 7
