What If I'm Struggling?
Early Intervention Is Key:
Don't wait until Part 7 to discover your documentation is insufficient
If something isn't working (dilemma, approach, understanding), address it early
Office hours exist specifically to help you course-correct
Common Struggles and Solutions:
"I don't know if I'm doing this right" → Schedule office hours to review your work; compare your depth to Gallery Walk peers
"My AI conversations feel shallow" → Push yourself to ask "why" more; share more context; explore discomfort
"I'm behind on framework explorations" → Create catch-up schedule; consider which frameworks can be briefer vs. deeper
"I can't tell if my thinking has changed" → Reread your Part 0-1 work; note places where you'd now say something different
Course Materials
Academic integrity means giving credit where it's due. Even though all course materials are Open Educational Resources (free and openly licensed), we still cite them properly. Why? Because citing isn't about copyright—it's about intellectual honesty. Authors deserve recognition for their ideas and work, regardless of whether they charge for access. Just as you'll document your thinking through AI transcripts, this course models proper attribution by citing all readings and showing you how to acknowledge sources—including AI conversations—in your own work.
Here is a bibliography of all materials used in this course, using APA 7th Edition guidelines:
Brusseau, J. (2012). The business ethics workshop. Saylor Foundation. https://resources.saylor.org/wwwresources/archived/site/textbooks/The%20Business%20Ethics%20Workshop.pdf  License: Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike (CC BY-NC-SA)
Holt, D. (2020). What is a moral (ethical) dilemma? In D. Holt, Ethics and society. Rebus Community. https://viva.pressbooks.pub/phi220ethics/chapter/what-is-an-ethical-dilemma/
License: Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International (CC BY)
Garlikov, R. (n.d.). The point of studying ethics (moral philosophy). http://www.garlikov.com/philosophy/ethpoint.htm No formal copyright notice on the website, but author states: "This work is available here free, so that those who cannot afford it can still have access to it"
Levin, N. (Ed.). (2019). Introduction to ethics: An open educational resource. N.G.E. Far Press. https://philarchive.org/archive/LEVITE-3 License: Creative Commons Attribution (CC BY)
Shea, B. (2023). Ethical explorations: Moral dilemmas in a universe of possibilities. https://mlpp.pressbooks.pub/ethicalexplorations/ Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International (CC BY-NC).
Citing AI Interactions (APA 7th Edition)
When citing AI-generated content or transcripts in this course, use APA 7th edition format. Include: (1) the AI tool developer/company name, (2) year of interaction, (3) AI tool name and model/version in brackets, (4) description of type, and (5) URL.
Example: Anthropic. (2024). Claude (Sonnet 3.5) [Large language model]. https://claude.ai
For in-text citations, use: (Anthropic, 2024). When submitting transcripts, include the full conversation as an appendix and cite specific exchanges by referencing the appendix location. Always document the complete date of your interaction within your transcript submission.
Data Privacy and Technology Safety
 
Data Privacy and Technology Use
This course uses several technologies that involve your personal data and intellectual work. Understanding how to protect your privacy while engaging authentically with course content is important.
Your Rights and Responsibilities
You have the right to understand what happens to the data you create in this course. You have the responsibility to make informed decisions about what personal information you share in course activities.
General Principle: Be thoughtful about sharing sensitive personal information in any online environment, even when that environment is designed for educational purposes.
AI Tools: Privacy Considerations
You will choose your own AI tool for this course (ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Copilot, or others). Different AI platforms have different privacy policies and data practices.
Platform
Free Account Data Use
Privacy Mode Available?
Educational Account Options
Key Privacy Features
ChatGPT
Conversations may train model unless opted out
Yes (chat history can be disabled)
ChatGPT Plus/Team have different policies
Can delete chat history; opt-out available
Claude
Conversations not used for training
Yes (temporary chats available)
Claude Pro has enhanced privacy
Clear data retention policies
