Connected to Google account data
Settings-dependent
Through Google Workspace
Integrated with Google privacy controls
Microsoft Copilot
Varies by version
Enterprise versions available
Through Microsoft 365 Education
Different tiers with different policies

What You Should Know:
Data Retention:
Most AI platforms store your conversation history unless you explicitly use privacy modes or delete conversations
Some platforms use conversations to improve their models (though educational accounts often have protections)
Conversation data may be retained even after you stop using the service
What This Means for Your Course Work:
Your AI conversations will contain personal reflections on real ethical dilemmas from your life
Consider what level of detail you're comfortable having potentially stored by the AI platform
When discussing your dilemma, you can use pseudonyms for other people involved (e.g., "my supervisor," "a colleague") rather than real names
Avoid including identifying information about third parties (full names, specific company names, detailed location information) unless you're comfortable with that data being potentially retained
Privacy-Protective Practices:
Check your chosen platform's privacy settings:
Many AI tools offer "privacy mode" or options to prevent conversation storage
Educational or paid accounts often have stronger privacy protections than free accounts
Review privacy settings when you first set up your account
Be strategic about what you share:
Your dilemma should be authentic, but you can describe situations without identifying specific individuals
Example: Instead of "My manager Sarah Thompson at ABC Corporation asked me to..." write "My manager asked me to..."
Focus on the ethical complexity, not identifying details
Understand that your instructor will see your work:
You'll submit complete AI conversation transcripts to your Google Drive folder
Only Dr. Lambert will have access to these transcripts
These are part of your academic record and will be treated confidentially
Resources for comparing AI platform privacy:
[You would insert a link here to a comparison resource, or I can help you create one]
If you have concerns about privacy with your chosen AI tool, contact Dr. Lambert to discuss alternatives
Perusall: Collaborative Annotation
Who can see your annotations:
All students enrolled in TGE 1257 Spring 2026
Dr. Lambert (instructor)
Perusall platform administrators (per their privacy policy)
What this means:
Your annotations are part of a learning community—they're meant to be visible to classmates
Annotations become part of your academic record
Other students may reference or respond to your comments
Privacy tips:
You're annotating published philosophical texts, not sharing personal diaries
When connecting texts to personal experience, you can be authentic without oversharing identifying details
If you're uncomfortable with a comment you've posted, you can edit or delete it before the assignment deadline
Google Drive: Shared Folders
Who can access your folder:
Only you and Dr. Lambert
Google (as the platform provider, per their institutional privacy agreement with ISU)
What's shared:
All documents you create in your TGE 1257 shared folder
This includes AI transcripts, your conflict map, framework explorations, and self-assessment
Privacy protections:
Your folder is NOT visible to other students
ISU uses Google Workspace for Education, which has enhanced privacy protections beyond consumer Google accounts
Your work will not be used for commercial purposes or advertising
Best practices:
Keep all course work in your designated TGE 1257 folder for appropriate privacy settings
Don't share your folder with anyone other than Dr. Lambert
If you need to discuss folder access issues, contact Dr. Lambert
Idaho State University Policies
ISU is committed to protecting student data privacy in accordance with FERPA (Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act) and other applicable regulations.
Relevant policies:
ISU's Student Data Privacy Policy: https://www.isu.edu/ogc/privacy/
FERPA Information for Students: https://www.isu.edu/registrar/ferpa/
Your rights under FERPA:
Your educational records (including work in this course) are confidential
Dr. Lambert will not share your work with others without your consent, except as required by law or institutional policy
You have the right to review your educational records
What Dr. Lambert Does to Protect Your Privacy
Commitments:
I will access your Google Drive folder only for the purpose of providing feedback and assessing your learning
I will not share your AI transcripts, dilemmas, or personal reflections with others unless required by law (e.g., mandatory reporting obligations)
If I want to use anonymized examples from student work for teaching or research purposes, I will request explicit permission
I will secure any downloaded copies of your work and delete them after grading is complete
Mandatory Reporting Obligations:
Like all ISU faculty, I am a mandatory reporter for:
Child abuse or endangerment
Threats of harm to self or others
Sexual misconduct or Title IX violations
If your ethical dilemma involves situations that trigger mandatory reporting, I am legally required to report to appropriate authorities. If you have questions about whether your dilemma might involve mandatory reporting, you can discuss this with me confidentially during office hours before including details in your written work.
Questions or Concerns About Privacy?
If you have questions about:
How to protect your privacy while completing assignments authentically
Privacy policies of specific AI tools
What information is safe to include in your work
Technical privacy settings for any course tool
Please contact Dr. Lambert during office hours or via email. I'm happy to discuss strategies for protecting your privacy while still engaging meaningfully with the course.
You can also contact:
ISU IT Security: 282-HELP (4357) or help@isu.edu for technical questions about data security
Student Legal Services: ISU Office of General Counsel for questions about your rights regarding educational data
Acknowledgment
By continuing in this course, you acknowledge that:
You understand the data privacy considerations outlined above
You will make informed decisions about what personal information to share in course activities
You will take responsibility for reviewing and understanding the privacy policies of the AI tool you choose
You understand that while ISU and your instructor take steps to protect your privacy, no online environment is completely secure
