Course Communications
Communicate with me via email, not through Canvas messaging.
Make sure emails have your class number and section in the subject line, along with a brief cue to the subject (e.g. “1101-A2 Missing for Tech Expo”). In addition, include an opening salutation, a brief message—including any action desired/expected, and a closing salutation (including your name). Emails without these elements may not receive a response.
Emails sent during business hours (8–5 M–F) will receive responses as soon as possible (my presence in other classes or meetings may postpone these somewhat). Emails sent after hours will generally receive responses the next business morning— although urgent requests (as determined by me from the content of your message) may prompt earlier response.
Should you contact me in person, during class, about a need or concern—and we come to some agreement about that— I ask that you email me afterward (as promptly as possible) to remind me for our mutual benefit.
Course Technical Expectations
In order to successfully complete this course, you will need to be able to do the following:
Use a mouse or other input device
Navigate within the Moodle learning management system
Use email with attachments
Create and submit files in commonly used word processing program formats
Copy and paste text within a document and from one file to another
Download and install software if necessary (such as the Firefox internet browser)
Navigate a web page
Upload assignments using a browse function
If you are unsure or unable to perform one or more of these tasks, it is critical that you contact me immediately, so I can arrange training and support for you. Failure to meet these expectations will significantly hamper your ability to complete this course.
General Education Objectives
Recognize and describe humanistic, historical, or artistic works within problems and patterns of the human experience. (Not covered in this course)
Distinguish and apply terminologies, methodologies, processes, epistemologies, and traditions specific to the discipline(s).
Perceive and understand formal, conceptual, and technical elements specific to the discipline.
Analyze, evaluate, and interpret texts, objects, events, or ideas in their cultural, intellectual or historical contexts.
Interpret artistic and/or humanistic works through the creation of art or performance. (Not covered in this course)
Develop critical perspectives or arguments about the subject matter, grounded in evidence-based analysis.
Demonstrate self-reflection, intellectual elasticity, widened perspective, and respect for diverse viewpoints.
General Assignment Expectations
All activities, unless specifically directed otherwise, should be typed in a business font, such as Arial, Helvetica, Times New Roman, Calibri, etc. with a font size of 12.
All activities, unless specifically directed otherwise, should be submitted through Canvas in their appropriate assignment link. If you submit an assignment in the wrong place, I will try to inform you. It is up to you to correct any incorrectly submitted assignments.
One document per assignment; do not submit multiple assignments in one document. I will not look for, nor will I correct or accept, additional assignments submitted this way.
Proper spelling and grammar are expected on all submissions, as if they were being considered for business correspondence.
Spelling and grammar are grounds for determining a submission does not meet expectations.
All submissions should use complete sentence format. Incomplete sentences are grounds for determining a submission does not meet expectations.
Each assignment contains a specific list of activities or questions. Review of the submission will focus on whether the responses accurately address these activities or questions.
